{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17611831","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17611831"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:16:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:16:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16247"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16247","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16247"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.48,0.19,0.19,0.15,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8938"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65153"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8938","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8938"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16247"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50589"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7567"},{"type":"tags","id":"8133"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21269"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21271"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65153","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/65153"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ELaboratory reference ranges vary with age, particularly in neonates and growing children.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following laboratory values is higher in neonates compared to adults?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Alkaline phosphatase","Albumin","Creatinine","Glucose","Sodium"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlkaline phosphatase\u003C/strong\u003E is significantly higher in neonates and children compared to adults. This is because ALP is associated with bone growth and development, and neonates experience rapid skeletal development during the first few months of life. The elevated ALP levels reflect the active bone turnover and growth processes in neonates. The enzyme is produced by bone, liver, and other tissues, with the bone isoenzyme predominating during growth phases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlbumin\u003C/strong\u003E levels are actually lower in neonates compared to adults\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECreatinine\u003C/strong\u003E is lower in neonates due to lower muscle mass\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGlucose\u003C/strong\u003E tends to be lower in neonates compared to adults\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESodium\u003C/strong\u003E levels are similar between neonates and adults\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding age-specific reference ranges is crucial for accurate interpretation of laboratory results in paediatric patients.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Alkaline phosphatase levels are physiologically elevated in growing children due to increased osteoblast activity.","Normal alkaline phosphatase values vary significantly with age, being highest during periods of rapid bone growth.","Other age-related laboratory differences in neonates include higher haematocrit, lower glucose, and higher calcium levels compared to adults."],"references":["Lowe D, Sanvictores T, Zubair M, et al. Alkaline Phosphatase. [Updated 2023 Oct 29]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK459201/","Sharma U, Pal D, Prasad R. Alkaline phosphatase: an overview. Indian J Clin Biochem. 2014 Jul;29(3):269-78. doi: 10.1007/s12291-013-0408-y. Epub 2013 Nov 26. PMID: 24966474; PMCID: PMC4062654.","Cannalire G, Pilloni S, Esposito S, Biasucci G, Di Franco A, Street ME. Alkaline phosphatase in clinical practice in childhood: Focus on rickets. Front Endocrinol (Lausanne). 2023 Feb 2;14:1111445. doi: 10.3389/fendo.2023.1111445. PMID: 36817604; PMCID: PMC9931734.","Singh, V. (2022). Textbook of clinical embryology, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Lissauer, T., \u0026 Carroll, W. (Eds.). (2021). Illustrated Textbook of Paediatrics E-Book: Illustrated Textbook of Paediatrics E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50589"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16247"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50589","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/50589"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-25T16:39:33+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-25T16:39:59+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8938"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65153"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":